Obscene Stalker: It Holds in Darkness! (, Waisetsu Sutkaa: Kurayami de Idaite!?) is a 2002 Japanese pink film in the suspense genre, directed by Yutaka Ikejima. It was chosen as the eighth best pink release of the year, and lead actress Hotaru Hazuki was given a Best Actress award at the Pink Grand Prix ceremony.[2] Natsuki is a blind girl on whose testimony Takechi investigates the murder of her friend Yko.[3] Yutaka Ikejima filmed Obscene Stalker: It Holds in Darkness! for his own Cement Match production company, and it was released theatrically in Japan by Shinth on March 29, 2002.[1] Max-A's release of Obscene Stalker: It Holds in Darkness! to home video in VHS format on its Gash label, on February 18, 2003 shows the film's English title.[5] Shinth gave the film a second theatrical release on August 9, 2005 under the title Super Obscene Mystery: Stalker in the Darkness (, Ch Waisetsu Misuterii: Kurayami no Sutkaa?).[6] 1. A Saloon Wet with Beautiful Women (Kashihara) 2. Lost Virgin: Resigned to Paid Dating (Sat) 3. Office Lady's Sexual Confession: Burning Love Affair (Ikejima) 4. Wive's Meeting Place: Wives Sexual Tendencies the Husband Does Not Know (Enomoto) 5. Shameful Family: Pin Down Technique (Meike) 6. Adulterous Wife: Dizzy (Tajiri) 7. Molester's Bus 2: Heat of the Over Thirty (Araki) 8. Obscene Stalker: It Holds in Darkness! (Ikejima) 9. Delivery Health Girl: The Moisture of Silken Skin (Ikejima) 10. Older Woman: Hakata Beauty's Shyness (Araki) Director: Mitsuru Meike New Director: Tatsuro Kashihara Actress: Koharu Yamasaki  Hotaru Hazuki  Yuki New Actress: Misaki Wakamiya  Nikki Sasaki  Ruri Tachibana  Noriko Masaki Actor: Yasushi Takemoto  Kazuhiro Sano Screenplay: Tatsuro Kashihara Technical Award (Cinematography): Takuya Hasegawa Special Award: Fukuoka kura Theater (1988) (1989) (1990) (1991) (1992) (1993) (1994) (1995) (1996) (1997) (1998) (1999) (2000) (2001) (2002) (2003) (2004) (2005) (2006) (2007) (2008) (2009)
